        <row bottom="minor"><cell>Skypilot (native)</cell><cell>190.76</cell><cell>13.06</cell><cell>25</cell></row>
        <row><cell><em>Differences</em></cell><cell><em>1.36</em></cell><cell><em>4.70</em></cell><cell><em>25</em></cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <figure xml:id="fig-flowering-plots">
      <caption>The flowering-day data. Left: a histogram of the difference between the first-flowering days (skypilot minus willow). Right: a case-profile plot of days of first flowering (unfilled points and dashed lines indicate earlier or same dates for willow).</caption>
      <image source="placeholder.jpeg" width="100%"/>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-pain-relieving-tape">
    <title>Example: pain-relieving tape</title>
    <p>
      <xref ref="naugle2021effect"/> studied the effect of using Kinesio Tape to alleviate pain in athletes. Pain was measured by applying a slow constant rate of pressure on the left arm, and subjects pressed a button when the sensation moved from pressure to pain. The pressure at which this occurred was recorded. This was repeated <m>5</m> minutes before applying the tape, <m>5</m> minutes after applying the tape, and again <m>15</m><ndash/><m>20</m> minutes after applying the tape.
    </p>
    <p>
      Figure <xref ref="fig-tape-repeated"/> shows the reported pain for <m>16</m> subjects. A summary table is shown in Table <xref ref="tab-tape-table"/>. The pain thresholds are increasing slightly as time progresses.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-tape-repeated">
      <caption>Pain threshold (left arm) at three time points when using Kinesio Tape, without applying tension, for <m>n = 16</m> subjects. The filled, black points represent the means for each time point.</caption>
      <image source="placeholder.jpeg" width="80%"/>
    </figure>

    <table xml:id="tab-tape-table">
      <title>A numerical summary of the tape data: pain thresholds in kPa.</title>
      <tabular halign="center" top="medium" bottom="medium">
        <col/><col/><col/><col/><col/><col/>
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell><alert>Mean (kPa)</alert></cell>
          <cell><alert>Std dev. (kPa)</alert></cell>
          <cell><alert>Sample size</alert></cell>
          <cell><alert>Mean increase from Pre</alert></cell>
          <cell><alert>SD of increase from Pre</alert></cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>Pre: 5 min</cell><cell>446.5</cell><cell>175.18</cell><cell>16</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
        <row><cell>Post: 5 min</cell><cell>479.6</cell><cell>199.61</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>33.0</cell><cell>73.93</cell></row>
        <row><cell>Post: 15<ndash/>20 min</cell><cell>506.9</cell><cell>214.36</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>60.3</cell><cell>102.72</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-chap13-summary">
    <title>Chapter summary</title>
    <p>
      Quantitative data measured within individuals can be summarised using a histogram of differences when the variable is measured or observed twice, or a case-profile plot (with two or more measurement or observations per individual). A summary table should show the numerical summaries for the quantitative variable at each measurement or observation and for appropriate changes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <reading-questions xml:id="sec-chap13-quick-review">
    <title>Quick review questions</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>Are the following statements <em>true</em> or <em>false</em>?</p>
    </introduction>
    <exercise xml:id="rq-ch13-1">
      <statement><p>A histogram of the differences is only appropriate for within two within-individuals measurements or observations.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>True.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="rq-ch13-2">
      <statement><p>A case-profile plot is only appropriate for showing changes for two within-individuals measurements or observations.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>False; a case-profile plot can be used for <em>two or more</em> within-individual comparisons.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="rq-ch13-3">
      <statement><p>The median and IQR are <em>not</em> appropriate for summarising differences.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>False; use whatever numerical summaries are appropriate.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="rq-ch13-4">
      <statement><p>Explaining <em>how</em> the differences are computed is important.</p></statement>
      <answer><p>True.</p></answer>
    </exercise>
  </reading-questions>

  <exercises xml:id="sec-summarise-within-exercises">
    <introduction>
      <p>Answers to odd-numbered exercises are given at the end of the book.</p>
    </introduction>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-compare-within-insulation">
      <statement>
      <p>
        [<em>Dataset</em>: <c>Insulation</c>] The <em>Electricity Council</em> in Bristol wanted to determine if a certain type of wall-cavity insulation reduced average energy consumption in winter <xref ref="data-OpenUni-insulationBA"/><xref ref="data-hand-handbook"/>:
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>In Bristol homes, what is the <em>mean reduction</em> in energy consumption after adding home insulation?</p>
      </blockquote>
      <ol>
        <li><p>What are the individuals (units of analysis)?</p></li>
        <li><p>Explain why this study uses a within-individuals comparison.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use the collected data (shown below) to sketch a case-profile plot.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use the data to sketch a histogram of the differences.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use software or a calculator to prepare a summary table.</p></li>
      </ol>

      <table xml:id="tab-insulation-data">
        <title>The house insulation data: energy consumption before and after adding insulation, and the energy saving (all in MWh).</title>
        <tabular halign="center" top="medium" bottom="medium">
          <col/><col/><col/><col/>
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell><alert>Home</alert></cell>
            <cell><alert>Before</alert></cell>
            <cell><alert>After</alert></cell>
            <cell><alert>Saving</alert></cell>
          </row>
          <row><cell>A</cell><cell>12.1</cell><cell>12.0</cell><cell>0.1</cell></row>
          <row><cell>B</cell><cell>11.0</cell><cell>10.6</cell><cell>0.4</cell></row>
          <row><cell>C</cell><cell>14.1</cell><cell>13.4</cell><cell>0.7</cell></row>
          <row><cell>D</cell><cell>13.8</cell><cell>11.2</cell><cell>2.6</cell></row>
          <row><cell>E</cell><cell>15.5</cell><cell>15.3</cell><cell>0.2</cell></row>
          <row><cell>F</cell><cell>12.2</cell><cell>13.6</cell><cell><m>-</m>1.4</cell></row>
          <row><cell>G</cell><cell>12.8</cell><cell>12.6</cell><cell>0.2</cell></row>
          <row><cell>H</cell><cell>9.9</cell><cell>8.8</cell><cell>1.1</cell></row>
          <row><cell>I</cell><cell>10.8</cell><cell>9.6</cell><cell>1.2</cell></row>
          <row><cell>J</cell><cell>12.7</cell><cell>12.4</cell><cell>0.3</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-compare-within-exercises-captopril">
      <statement>
      <p>
        [<em>Dataset</em>: <c>Captopril</c>] In a study of hypertension <xref ref="data-hand-handbook"/><xref ref="data-macgregor-essential"/>, <m>15</m> patients were given a drug (Captopril) and their systolic blood pressure measured (in mm Hg) immediately before and two hours after being given the drug (Table <xref ref="tab-ci-captopril-data"/>).
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Explain why this study uses a within-individuals comparison.</p></li>
        <li><p>Construct a histogram of the differences.</p></li>
        <li><p>Construct a case-profile plot for the data.</p></li>
      </ol>

